  "text": "The group SH of L-cysteine is oxidized (4) and two molecules are absorbed at the electrode surface (5) and forming a L-cystine (1). This mechanism can be verified by the electrochemical measurements ( Figure 1 ) performed under experimental conditions specified in the experimental section. Figure 1 shows the cyclic voltammograms of covalent modification of glassy carbon surface electrode using L-cysteine solutions prepared in PBS and HCl as supporting electrolyte. This Figure indicates an irreversible oxidation peak at ca. +0.7 V at the first segment, which implies that L-cysteine (1) was oxidized to L-cystine [CITATION_1] , and indicating that the species obtained after the first electron transfer undergoes a chemical reaction. The modification process was almost finished after three cycles. On the other hand, other irreversible oxidation peak was observed at ca. +1.6 V with further voltammetric cycling. This behaviour was achieved at both GC electrodes using the two L-cysteine solutions; however, the oxidation of L-cysteine was faster using PBS as supporting electrolyte than the other one. The oxidation peak response decreased quickly with the successive scanning till the third times ( Figure 1a , Cys-MGC PBS electrode). This is attributed to the passivation of the electrode related to the grafting of cysteine on the surface of GC electrode. Nevertheless, other factors due to be taken into consideration about the L-cysteine oxidation and adsorption on the electrode surface, which are discussed in the next section.",
